1.14:
I hate your New Moons and prescribed festivals.
They have become a burden to me;
I am tired of putting up with them.

1.25:
I will turn my hand against you
and will burn away your dross completely;
I will remove all your impurities.

2.8:
Their land is full of worthless idols;
they worship the work of their hands,
what their fingers have made.

2.11:
The pride of mankind will be humbled,
and human loftiness will be brought low;
the Lord alone will be exalted on that day.

2.17:
The pride of mankind will be brought low,
and human loftiness will be humbled;
the Lord alone will be exalted on that day.

3.24:
Instead of perfume there will be a stench;
instead of a belt, a rope;
instead of beautifully styled hair, baldness;
instead of fine clothes, sackcloth;
instead of beauty, branding.

5.29:
Their roaring is like a lion’s;
they roar like young lions;
they growl and seize their prey
and carry it off,
and no one can rescue it.

6.3:
And one called to another:
Holy, holy, holy is the Lord of Armies;
his glory fills the whole earth.

6.10:
Make the minds of these people dull;
deafen their ears and blind their eyes;
otherwise they might see with their eyes
and hear with their ears,
understand with their minds,
turn back, and be healed.

8.9:
Band together, peoples, and be broken;
pay attention, all you distant lands;
prepare for war, and be broken;
prepare for war, and be broken.

8.13:
You are to regard only the Lord of Armies as holy.
Only he should be feared;
only he should be held in awe.

8.15:
Many will stumble over these;
they will fall and be broken;
they will be snared and captured.

12.2:
Indeed, God is my salvation;
I will trust him and not be afraid,
for the Lord, the Lord himself,
is my strength and my song.
He has become my salvation.”

13.8:
They will be horrified;
pain and agony will seize them;
they will be in anguish like a woman in labor.
They will look at each other,
their faces flushed with fear.

13.16:
Their children will be dashed to pieces before their eyes;
their houses will be looted,
and their wives raped.

13.18:
Their bows will cut young men to pieces.
They will have no compassion on offspring;
they will not look with pity on children.

14.10:
They all respond to you, saying,
“You too have become as weak as we are;
you have become like us!

14.24:
The Lord of Armies has sworn:
As I have purposed, so it will be;
as I have planned it, so it will happen.

15.3:
In its streets they wear sackcloth;
on its rooftops and in its public squares everyone wails,
falling down and weeping.

15.5:
My heart cries out over Moab,
whose fugitives flee as far as Zoar,
to Eglath-shelishiyah;
they go up the Ascent of Luhith weeping;
they raise a cry of destruction
on the road to Horonaim.

15.6:
The Waters of Nimrim are desolate;
the grass is withered, the foliage is gone,
and the vegetation has vanished.

17.2:
The cities of Aroer are abandoned;
they will be places for flocks.
They will lie down without fear.

19.6:
The channels will stink;
they will dwindle, and Egypt’s canals will be parched.
Reed and rush will wilt.

19.13:
The princes of Zoan have been fools;
the princes of Memphis are deceived.
Her tribal chieftains have led Egypt astray.

21.6:
For the Lord has said to me,
“Go, post a lookout;
let him report what he sees.

21.15:
For they have fled from swords,
from the drawn sword,
from the bow that is strung,
and from the stress of battle.

23.2:
Mourn, inhabitants of the coastland,
you merchants of Sidon;
your agents have crossed the sea

24.4:
The earth mourns and withers;
the world wastes away and withers;
the exalted people of the earth waste away.

24.7:
The new wine mourns;
the vine withers.
All the carousers now groan.

24.11:
In the streets they cry for wine.
All joy grows dark;
earth’s rejoicing goes into exile.

24.14:
They raise their voices, they sing out;
they proclaim in the west
the majesty of the Lord.

24.19:
The earth is completely devastated;
the earth is split open;
the earth is violently shaken.

25.1:
Lord, you are my God;
I will exalt you. I will praise your name,
for you have accomplished wonders,
plans formed long ago, with perfect faithfulness.

25.2:
For you have turned the city into a pile of rocks,
a fortified city, into ruins;
the fortress of barbarians is no longer a city;
it will never be rebuilt.

26.9:
I long for you in the night;
yes, my spirit within me diligently seeks you,
for when your judgments are in the land,
the inhabitants of the world will learn righteousness.

26.14:
The dead do not live;
departed spirits do not rise up.
Indeed, you have punished and destroyed them;
you have wiped out all memory of them.

26.16:
Lord, they went to you in their distress;
they poured out whispered prayers
because your discipline fell on them.

27.5:
Or let it take hold of my strength;
let it make peace with me—
make peace with me.

28.12:
He had said to them,
“This is the place of rest;
let the weary rest;
this is the place of repose.”
But they would not listen.

28.29:
This also comes from the Lord of Armies.
He gives wondrous advice;
he gives great wisdom.

29.3:
I will camp in a circle around you;
I will besiege you with earth ramps,
and I will set up my siege towers against you.

29.4:
You will be brought down;
you will speak from the ground,
and your words will come from low in the dust.
Your voice will be like that of a spirit from the ground;
your speech will whisper from the dust.

29.9:
Stop and be astonished;
blind yourselves and be blind!
They are drunk, but not with wine;
they stagger, but not with beer.

30.7:
Egypt’s help is completely worthless;
therefore, I call her:
Rahab Who Just Sits.

31.3:
Egyptians are men, not God;
their horses are flesh, not spirit.
When the Lord raises his hand to strike,
the helper will stumble
and the one who is helped will fall;
both will perish together.

31.5:
Like hovering birds,
so the Lord of Armies will protect Jerusalem;
by protecting it, he will rescue it;
by passing over it, he will deliver it.

31.8:
Then Assyria will fall,
but not by human sword;
a sword will devour him,
but not one made by man.
He will flee from the sword;
his young men will be put to forced labor.

32.7:
The scoundrel’s weapons are destructive;
he hatches plots to destroy the needy with lies,
even when the poor person says what is right.

32.17:
The result of righteousness will be peace;
the effect of righteousness
will be quiet confidence forever.

33.9:
The land mourns and withers;
Lebanon is ashamed and wilted.
Sharon is like a desert;
Bashan and Carmel shake off their leaves.

33.11:
You will conceive chaff;
you will give birth to stubble.
Your breath is fire that will consume you.

33.16:
he will dwell on the heights;
his refuge will be the rocky fortresses,
his food provided, his water assured.

34.3:
Their slain will be thrown out,
and the stench of their corpses will rise;
the mountains will flow with their blood.

34.9:
Edom’s streams will be turned into pitch,
her soil into sulfur;
her land will become burning pitch.

34.17:
He has cast the lot for them;
his hand allotted their portion with a measuring line.
They will possess it forever;
they will dwell in it from generation to generation.

35.6:
Then the lame will leap like a deer,
and the tongue of the mute will sing for joy,
for water will gush in the wilderness,
and streams in the desert;

38.10:
I said: In the prime of my life
I must go to the gates of Sheol;
I am deprived of the rest of my years.

38.17:
Indeed, it was for my own well-being
that I had such intense bitterness;
but your love has delivered me
from the Pit of destruction,
for you have thrown all my sins behind your back.

38.19:
The living, only the living can thank you,
as I do today;
a father will make your faithfulness known to children.

40.3:
A voice of one crying out:
Prepare the way of the Lord in the wilderness;
make a straight highway for our God in the desert.

40.7:
The grass withers, the flowers fade
when the breath of the Lord blows on them;
indeed, the people are grass.

40.15:
Look, the nations are like a drop in a bucket;
they are considered as a speck of dust on the scales;
he lifts up the islands like fine dust.

40.17:
All the nations are as nothing before him;
they are considered by him
as empty nothingness.

40.31:
but those who trust in the Lord
will renew their strength;
they will soar on wings like eagles;
they will run and not become weary,
they will walk and not faint.

41.10:
Do not fear, for I am with you;
do not be afraid, for I am your God.
I will strengthen you; I will help you;
I will hold on to you with my righteous right hand.

41.28:
When I look, there is no one;
there is no counselor among them;
when I ask them, they have nothing to say.

41.29:
Look, all of them are a delusion;
their works are nonexistent;
their images are wind and emptiness.

42.3:
He will not break a bruised reed,
and he will not put out a smoldering wick;
he will faithfully bring justice.

42.9:
The past events have indeed happened.
Now I declare new events;
I announce them to you before they occur.”

43.5:
Do not fear, for I am with you;
I will bring your descendants from the east,
and gather you from the west.

44.5:
This one will say, ‘I am the Lord’s’;
another will use the name of Jacob;
still another will write on his hand, ‘The Lord’s,’
and take on the name of Israel.”

44.15:
A person can use it for fuel.
He takes some of it and warms himself;
also he kindles a fire and bakes bread;
he even makes it into a god and worships it;
he makes an idol from it and bows down to it.

44.17:
He makes a god or his idol with the rest of it.
He bows down to it and worships;
he prays to it, “Save me, for you are my god.”

44.21:
Remember these things, Jacob,
and Israel, for you are my servant;
I formed you, you are my servant;
Israel, you will never be forgotten by me.

44.24:
This is what the Lord, your Redeemer who formed you from the womb, says:
I am the Lord, who made everything;
who stretched out the heavens by myself;
who alone spread out the earth;

44.25:
who destroys the omens of the false prophets
and makes fools of diviners;
who confounds the wise
and makes their knowledge foolishness;

44.26:
who confirms the message of his servant
and fulfills the counsel of his messengers;
who says to Jerusalem, “She will be inhabited,”
and to the cities of Judah, “They will be rebuilt,”
and I will restore her ruins;

45.7:
I form light and create darkness,
I make success and create disaster;
I am the Lord, who does all these things.

46.2:
The gods cower; they crouch together;
they are not able to rescue the burden,
but they themselves go into captivity.

46.7:
They lift it to their shoulder and bear it along;
they set it in its place, and there it stands;
it does not budge from its place.
They cry out to it but it doesn’t answer;
it saves no one from his trouble.

46.9:
Remember what happened long ago,
for I am God, and there is no other;
I am God, and no one is like me.

47.6:
I was angry with my people;
I profaned my possession,
and I handed them over to you.
You showed them no mercy;
you made your yoke very heavy on the elderly.

48.2:
For they are named after the holy city,
and lean on the God of Israel;
his name is the Lord of Armies.

48.3:
I declared the past events long ago;
they came out of my mouth; I proclaimed them.
Suddenly I acted, and they occurred.

48.7:
They have been created now, and not long ago;
you have not heard of them before today,
so you could not claim, ‘I already knew them!’

48.15:
I—I have spoken;
yes, I have called him;
I have brought him,
and he will succeed in his mission.

48.21:
They did not thirst
when he led them through the deserts;
he made water flow from the rock for them;
he split the rock, and water gushed out.

49.2:
He made my words like a sharp sword;
he hid me in the shadow of his hand.
He made me like a sharpened arrow;
he hid me in his quiver.

49.5:
And now, says the Lord,
who formed me from the womb to be his servant,
to bring Jacob back to him
so that Israel might be gathered to him;
for I am honored in the sight of the Lord,
and my God is my strength—

49.10:
They will not hunger or thirst,
the scorching heat or sun will not strike them;
for their compassionate one will guide them,
and lead them to springs.

49.12:
See, these will come from far away,
from the north and from the west,
and from the land of Sinim.

50.5:
The Lord God has opened my ear,
and I was not rebellious;
I did not turn back.

50.7:
The Lord God will help me;
therefore I have not been humiliated;
therefore I have set my face like flint,
and I know I will not be put to shame.

50.9:
In truth, the Lord God will help me;
who will condemn me?
Indeed, all of them will wear out like a garment;
a moth will devour them.

51.4:
Pay attention to me, my people,
and listen to me, my nation;
for instruction will come from me,
and my justice for a light to the nations.
I will bring it about quickly.

51.14:
The prisoner is soon to be set free;
he will not die and go to the Pit,
and his food will not be lacking.

53.6:
We all went astray like sheep;
we all have turned to our own way;
and the Lord has punished him
for the iniquity of us all.

54.2:
“Enlarge the site of your tent,
and let your tent curtains be stretched out;
do not hold back;
lengthen your ropes,
and drive your pegs deep.

55.7:
Let the wicked one abandon his way
and the sinful one his thoughts;
let him return to the Lord,
so he may have compassion on him,
and to our God, for he will freely forgive.

56.10:
Israel’s watchmen are blind, all of them,
they know nothing;
all of them are mute dogs,
they cannot bark;
they dream, lie down,
and love to sleep.

56.11:
These dogs have fierce appetites;
they never have enough.
And they are shepherds
who have no discernment;
all of them turn to their own way,
every last one for his own profit.

57.6:
Your portion is among the smooth stones of the wadi;
indeed, they are your lot.
You have even poured out a drink offering to them;
you have offered a grain offering;
should I be satisfied with these?

57.7:
You have placed your bed
on a high and lofty mountain;
you also went up there to offer sacrifice.

57.16:
For I will not accuse you forever,
and I will not always be angry;
for then the spirit would grow weak before me,
even the breath, which I have made.

57.17:
Because of his sinful greed I was angry,
so I struck him; I was angry and hid;
but he went on turning back to the desires of his heart.

57.18:
I have seen his ways, but I will heal him;
I will lead him and restore comfort
to him and his mourners,

57.20:
But the wicked are like the storm-tossed sea,
for it cannot be still,
and its water churns up mire and muck.

58.12:
Some of you will rebuild the ancient ruins;
you will restore the foundations laid long ago;
you will be called the repairer of broken walls,
the restorer of streets where people live.

58.13:
“If you keep from desecrating the Sabbath,
from doing whatever you want on my holy day;
if you call the Sabbath a delight,
and the holy day of the Lord honorable;
if you honor it, not going your own ways,
seeking your own pleasure, or talking business;

59.4:
No one makes claims justly;
no one pleads honestly.
They trust in empty and worthless words;
they conceive trouble and give birth to iniquity.

59.10:
We grope along a wall like the blind;
we grope like those without eyes.
We stumble at noon as though it were twilight;
we are like the dead among those who are healthy.

60.12:
For the nation and the kingdom
that will not serve you will perish;
those nations will be annihilated.

60.20:
Your sun will no longer set,
and your moon will not fade;
for the Lord will be your everlasting light,
and the days of your sorrow will be over.

60.21:
All your people will be righteous;
they will possess the land forever;
they are the branch I planted,
the work of my hands,
so that I may be glorified.

61.2:
to proclaim the year of the Lord’s favor,
and the day of our God’s vengeance;
to comfort all who mourn,

61.4:
They will rebuild the ancient ruins;
they will restore the former devastations;
they will renew the ruined cities,
the devastations of many generations.

61.6:
But you will be called the Lord’s priests;
they will speak of you as ministers of our God;
you will eat the wealth of the nations,
and you will boast in their riches.

61.8:
For I the Lord love justice;
I hate robbery and injustice;
I will faithfully reward my people
and make a permanent covenant with them.

62.4:
You will no longer be called Deserted,
and your land will not be called Desolate;
instead, you will be called My Delight Is in Her,
and your land Married;
for the Lord delights in you,
and your land will be married.

62.10:
Go out, go out through the city gates;
prepare a way for the people!
Build it up, build up the highway;
clear away the stones!
Raise a banner for the peoples.

63.6:
I crushed nations in my anger;
I made them drunk with my wrath
and poured out their blood on the ground.

64.8:
Yet Lord, you are our Father;
we are the clay, and you are our potter;
we all are the work of your hands.

64.10:
Your holy cities have become a wilderness;
Zion has become a wilderness,
Jerusalem a desolation.

65.6:
Look, it is written in front of me:
I will not keep silent, but I will repay;
I will repay them fully

66.3:
One person slaughters an ox, another kills a person;
one person sacrifices a lamb, another breaks a dog’s neck;
one person offers a grain offering, another offers pig’s blood;
one person offers incense, another praises an idol—
all these have chosen their ways
and delight in their abhorrent practices.

66.4:
So I will choose their punishment,
and I will bring on them what they dread
because I called and no one answered;
I spoke and they did not listen;
they did what was evil in my sight
and chose what I did not delight in.
